      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(slack): allow channel-id reads for name-allowlisted channels",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\r\nSlack action tools can target a channel by Slack channel ID, for example when reading a permalink or operating on a message outside the current thread. If an operator configured Slack channel access by human-readable channel name (for example `#allowed-channel`) with `dangerouslyAllowNameMatching` enabled, those channel-ID reads were rejected before the name allowlist could be applied.\r\n\r\nThat blocked legitimate read-like Slack actions such as reading messages, downloading files, listing pins, and listing reactions for channels that were configured as allowed by name.\r\n\r\n## How This Changes Behavior\r\n- Carries the current Slack channel name through threading tool context when the inbound transport provides it.\r\n- Uses the current channel name only when the target channel matches the current context, so one allowed context cannot authorize a different target channel.\r\n- Lazily resolves Slack conversation names through `conversations.info` when an action has only a channel ID and the account explicitly enabled name matching.\r\n- Re-checks read authorization with the resolved channel name and still fails closed if no allowed name is found.\r\n- Reuses the existing conversation info cache and returns names from that helper.\r\n\r\n## Evidence\r\n- `pnpm test:extension slack` — 101 files / 1334 tests passed.\r\n- `pnpm vitest run extensions/slack/src/action-runtime.test.ts extensions/slack/src/channel-type.test.ts` — 2 files / 74 tests passed.\r\n- `pnpm tsgo:extensions` — passed.\r\n- `git diff --check upstream/main...HEAD` — passed.\r\n- Added synthetic-fixture coverage for:\r\n  - current-context channel-name authorization of a matching channel ID;\r\n  - rejecting a different target channel even when the current context has an allowed name;\r\n  - resolving a channel name via `conversations.info` before failing an allowlist read;\r\n  - resolving a name-keyed allow before applying wildcard fallback denial;\r\n  - returning conversation names from the Slack channel-type helper.\r\n\r\nNot sure if this is acceptable proof, but in the past month, I had multiple OpenClaws on different machines collaborate with one another via a shared whitelisted Slack channel.\r\n\r\nRecently (as in the past ~3-5 days), after I upgraded to 2026.6.8, the ability for me to have bot-to-bot conversations went away.\r\n\r\nMy use case was Bot A does dev work on a repo; Bot B does deployment of a said PR to servers C it has access to. A does not have access to C, but can do so indirectly through B.\r\n\r\nExample of it working from the past month:\r\n<img width=\"638\" height=\"902\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/b63d8e17-bfae-4bd4-a727-41e83d2a0bea\" />\r\n\r\nExample of it NOT working:\r\n<img width=\"630\" height=\"580\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/4c0080e6-b04c-4141-a9fc-5f0b1ce169b2\" />\r\n\r\nExample of it working again after this patch:\r\nI'm having a bit of difficulty patching the source, reinstalling OpenClaw from source, and then generating this proof... As it's 6am now and I haven't slept, I'll have to try to resume this later.\r\n\r\n## Privacy / Fixture Notes\r\nAll examples in this PR use fabricated Slack fixtures such as `#allowed-channel`, `C0123456789`, and `C9876543210`; no private workspace channel names, channel IDs, user IDs, or message timestamps are included.\r\n",
        "branch": "fix/slack-read-allowlist-channel-name-public",
        "head_sha": "ee834023a27bd88d5ce71b5c3c271c90b2038804",
